1. What is the difference between a block element and an inline element? 
Give few examples of block and inline tags which we have in HTML.

1. Block-level elements:
    - Block-level elements typically start on a new line and take up the full width available to them.
    - They create a "block" of content, which means that other elements cannot appear to their left or right unless they are floated or positioned.
    - Block-level elements can have both width and height specified.
    - Examples of block-level elements: **`<div>`**, **`<p>`**, **`<h1>`** to **`<h6>`**, **`<ul>`**, **`<ol>`**, **`<li>`**, **`<form>`**, **`<header>`**, **`<footer>`**, **`<section>`**, **`<nav>`**, **`<article>`**, etc.

2. Inline elements:
    - Inline elements do not start on a new line and only take up the necessary width to display their content.
    - They flow within the surrounding text and allow other elements to appear to their left and right.
    - Inline elements cannot have width and height specified; they automatically adjust to the size of their content.
    - Examples of inline elements: **`<span>`**, **`<a>`**, **`<strong>`**, **`<em>`**, **`<img>`**, **`<input>`**, **`<label>`**, **`<button>`**, **`<select>`**, **`<textarea>`**, **`<code>`**, etc.


2. In how many ways you can declare CSS to an HTML ?

a. direct in tag : inline style
<h1 style="color:red">some text</h1>

b. create the style tag called Internal CSS:
<head>
  <style>
    p {
      color: red;
      font-size: 18px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <p>This is some text.</p>
</body>

c.  External CSS ; create the external css file by using .css and link them 
<head>
  <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="styles.css"> put here your css file name 
</head>

