4. What are CSS positions? What are the position types in CSS? What is the default position property in CSS?
CSS positions determine how an element is positioned within its parent container 
Eg index.html
 
a. static position (default) : the normal position of an HTML elements as per the document it is now shown beacuse the default behaviour of html elements is static

b. Relative:
- The **`relative`** position type allows you to position an element relative to its normal position.
- When an element is positioned relatively, it can be moved using the **`top`**, **`bottom`**, **`left`**, and **`right`** properties.
- Relative positioning does not affect the position of other elements on the page.
.box {
  position: relative;
  top: 10px; /* Move 10 pixels down */
  left: 20px; /* Move 20 pixels to the right */
}

c. Absolute:
Absolutely positioned elements are like free-floating objects that are taken out of the normal document flow.
Absolutely positioned elements can overlap with other elements.
You can use top, left, right, and bottom properties to position the element from the edges of its containing block.
.popup {
  position: absolute;
  top: 100px; /* Position 100 pixels from the top edge */
  left: 50%; /* Position at the middle horizontally */
  transform: translateX(-50%); /* Center horizontally */
}


d. Fixed:
Fixed positioned elements are removed from the normal document flow and are not affected by scrolling.
They remain fixed in their specified position even when the page is scrolled.

e. 5. Sticky:
    - The **`sticky`** position type is a hybrid of **`relative`** and **`fixed`**.
    - It positions an element based on its normal position in the document flow until a specified threshold is reached.
    - Once the threshold is reached during scrolling, the element behaves like a **`fixed`** positioned element and remains fixed in its position.



